// Figure 6.3: Checkout Flow - Synchronous Phase
// Checkout MFE → API Gateway → Basket Service → Redis → RabbitMQ → 202 Accepted

// ==================== ACTORS ====================
Browser [icon: chrome, color: blue]
Checkout MFE [icon: shopping-cart, color: purple]
API Gateway [icon: aws-api-gateway, color: red]
Basket Service [icon: shopping-cart, color: green]
Redis [icon: redis, color: red]
RabbitMQ [icon: rabbitmq, color: yellow]

// ==================== PHASE 1: CHECKOUT INITIATION ====================
// 1. From Checkout micro-frontend, user submits checkout form
Browser > Checkout MFE : Submit checkout form
// Form data: shipping address, payment details, contact info
Checkout MFE > Checkout MFE : Validate form data
Checkout MFE > Checkout MFE : Prepare checkout request
// Payload: { userName, shippingAddress, paymentMethod, cardDetails }
Checkout MFE > API Gateway : POST /Basket/Checkout
// Request includes cart items and checkout details

// ==================== PHASE 2: BASKET SERVICE PROCESSING ====================
// 2. Ocelot Gateway routes to Basket Service
API Gateway > API Gateway : Route to Basket Service
API Gateway > Basket Service : Forward to /api/v1/Basket/Checkout

// 2a. Basket Service retrieves cart from Redis
Basket Service > Redis : GET basket:{userName}
Redis > Basket Service : Return cart data
// Cart includes: items, totals, discounts

// 2b. Basket Service validates cart contents and totals
Basket Service > Basket Service : Validate cart not empty
Basket Service > Basket Service : Validate totals match
Basket Service > Basket Service : Validate item quantities
// Validation ensures data integrity before checkout

// 2c. Basket Service publishes BasketCheckoutEvent to RabbitMQ
Basket Service > Basket Service : Create BasketCheckoutEvent
// Event: { userName, items, totalPrice, shippingAddress, paymentMethod }
Basket Service > RabbitMQ : Publish BasketCheckoutEvent
// Asynchronous, fire-and-forget
RabbitMQ > RabbitMQ : Queue event for processing
RabbitMQ > Basket Service : Event queued successfully

// 2d. Basket Service deletes cart from Redis (local transaction)
Basket Service > Redis : DEL basket:{userName}
Redis > Basket Service : Cart deleted successfully
// Local transaction ensures cart removal

// 2e. Returns 202 Accepted to client immediately
Basket Service > API Gateway : HTTP 202 Accepted
// Immediate response, order processing continues async
API Gateway > Checkout MFE : HTTP 202 Accepted
Checkout MFE > Checkout MFE : Show "Order processing" message
Checkout MFE > Browser : Display order confirmation
// User can continue browsing while order processes

// ==================== KEY COMPONENTS ====================
// Checkout: Checkout.tsx (checkout form)
// Checkout: useCheckoutBasket hook (basket/hooks.ts)
// Backend: Ocelot Gateway (routing)
// Backend: Basket.API/Controllers/BasketController.cs (Checkout endpoint)
// Backend: Basket.API/EventBus (RabbitMQ publisher)
// Backend: Redis (cart storage)

// ==================== SYNCHRONOUS PHASE CHARACTERISTICS ====================
// - User receives immediate feedback (202 Accepted)
// - Cart deleted synchronously (local Redis transaction)
// - Event published asynchronously (fire-and-forget)
// - No waiting for order creation
// - Improved user experience (non-blocking)

